Local Engagement as a Countermeasure against Populism
PARIS – The parties that once dominated Western democracies have been shaken at their core.
Many – including in France, Italy, Greece, and the United Kingdom – have suffered crushing electoral defeats.
Others have changed so drastically that only the name remains.
The Republican Party of US President Donald Trump has little in common with that of former President Ronald Reagan.
These developments resemble each other everywhere in the West.
The leaderships of once dominant parties swing between denial and despair, while populists fish out their traditional supporters.
Some refuse to recognize a legitimate reason for their defeat and dismiss their opponents' supporters as "pitiable," as Hillary Clinton did shortly before she lost to Trump in 2016; others, in the face of the populist flood, are too scared to launch a counterattack.
Yet neither denial nor self-satisfaction will resolve the stalemate in the political situation.
The Progressives must regroup, and this begins with diagnosing the shortcomings of the traditional parties.
A part of the problem is that the traditional parties have not recognized the real issues of our time.
Still trapped on the old ideological battlegrounds, they ignored the declining social mobility, the intensifying environmental crises, the increasing geographic inequality, tensions regarding multiculturalism, and other issues that actually matter to voters.
Decades ago, they were the vanguard.
Today, they are alone in the forest, wondering where everyone else has gone.
The social sciences might have an answer as to why the mainstream has strayed from the path.
The gap between her objective analysis of reality and the policies of governments has widened into an abyss.
In most Western countries, economists have long been aware of the growing disparity in income and other indicators between some wealthy cities benefiting from globalization and the rest of the country.
Yet before the government of French President Emmanuel Macron did so, no national prime minister had implemented tax cuts based on residence.
As a result of this policy, 1% of France's GDP is now primarily redistributed to the poorest parts of the country.
Traditional parties could also learn something by listening directly to voters rather than only through the filters of media and polling institutes.
In the year 2016, Macron's movement En Marche! started with the largest door-to-door survey in French history.
What the voters told the questioners then became the basis of Macron's presidential campaign.
For example, "La Grande Marche" had collected countless statements from women about harassment more than a year before the revelations about Harvey Weinstein's alleged sexual advances against women, and Macron promised to address the issue if he were elected.
At that time, Macron's stance made him a target of jokes by his opponents; however, the laughter of those opponents quickly faded with the emergence of the #MeToo era.
However, a precise understanding of society alone is not enough.
The traditional parties also suffer from poor organization.
They long believed that modern politics should be organized around elections, where activists distribute flyers at intervals and cheer on the candidates.
This was less cynicism than a symptom of an approach that sees democracy as a marketplace consisting of state providers (the government) and consumers (the citizens).
According to this view, the sole purpose of a party is to seize and retain power.
It is no wonder that citizens and even party members feel ignored between elections.
Despite these weaknesses, the established parties had a number of advantages that delayed their collapse.
In recent years, they had a technological edge over less established opponents, and they were the only political actors with organized voter groups that could mobilize people to elections, organize protests, and start petitions.
But this model no longer holds.
Citizens today refuse to be mere consumers of state policy.
Along with a higher level of education came new demands for participation.
The voters want to be treated as political actors and not as pawns in the chess game of others.
Moreover, governments themselves are no longer the only providers of political measures.
This is one of the harsh lessons we had to learn in the two years we worked alongside Macron in the Élysée Palace.
The most important political challenges today – climate change, religious extremism, digital upheavals, and gender equality – do not allow for solutions from national governments alone.
These challenges require profound cultural changes and, in most cases, measures on subnational and supranational levels.
And finally, technology has lowered the barriers to political participation, meaning that traditional parties can no longer rely on the incumbent advantage and entrenched support networks.
Whoever can handle Google, Twitter, and Facebook well no longer needs a party apparatus that has been around for centuries.
Political movements must be reorganized accordingly.
The focus should be on concrete measures and not just on elections.
The formal administrative structure of a party should serve as an administrative "back office"; the front office should be staffed by people on the ground.
At La République En Marche! we refer to these as local civic projects.
These can range from after-school reading courses and integration programs for immigrants to cooperative vegetable gardens and digital training for seniors.
In any case, it is about offering solutions tailored to local problems and thus strengthening communities.
Such projects should today be seen as indispensable complements to state policy.
In the future, a party's ability to offer rewarding ways for political and local community engagement will be essential to its appeal.
And by daily demonstrating their reform policy "live," the parties have already prepared the ground for success on election day.
If voters refuse to listen to what you have to say, the answer is not to shout louder.
This is the hard lesson that traditional parties have learned.
Only those who demonstrate a commitment to improving people's lives, rather than simply winning elections, can win people over to their side.
Re-establishing the connection to the concerns of voters therefore goes hand in hand with adapting party organizations.
To offer a successful alternative to populism, we need progressive politics at the local level.
